      <title>RE: HowTo use LDAP/ActiveDirectory for Authentication and Authorization</title>
      <link>http://community.zenoss.org/docs/DOC-2510#comments-6433</link>
      <description>&lt;!-- [DocumentBodyStart:33aaf228-8a48-4583-970f-989e46d92158] --&gt;&lt;div class="jive-rendered-content"&gt;&lt;p&gt;For those of you running into the 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'instancehome' error:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="min-height: 8pt; height: 8pt; padding: 0px;"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is likely because you used the stack installer on centos 6, which handles python modules a bit differently.&amp;#160; If you installed via the "python setup.py install" command, then you will get this error - regardless of if you are running as the zenoss user or not.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The proper way to install modules, if you've installed from a recent stack build, is via "/opt/zenoss/bin/easy_install [pythonpkg.tar.gz]" - If you do this, then you can get it working.&amp;#160; I stuck with as close of a version as possible to this document for all of the modules.&amp;#160; I did have to make a couple of changes in addition - mostly changing the groupid_attr property to "name" instead of "objectGUID" for the AD module (role mapping was broken until i did this)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="min-height: 8pt; height: 8pt; padding: 0px;"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I was having all for the 'instancehome' errors until I stumbled on tho this...&amp;#160; It took a bit to figure out, as this was the first time I used the autodeploy - I had always done it manually before.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;!-- [DocumentBodyEnd:33aaf228-8a48-4583-970f-989e46d92158] --&gt;</description>
